{
  "answer": "Both Manu (unknown-manusmrti-347b76, corpus chapter 4, containing verses Mn_3.122–3.286) and Viṣṇu (unknown-visnu-smrti-27f0d8, chapters 73–80) give instructions on śrāddha foods and days, but Viṣṇu is substantially more specific on both counts.\n\n**FOODS**\n\nManu (Mn_3.267–3.273): Lists foods by duration of ancestral satisfaction — sesame seeds, rice, barley, black lentils, water, roots, or fruit satisfy for one month; fish (2), deer (3), mutton (4), birds (5), goat (6), spotted deer (7), black antelope (8), Ruru deer (9), wild boar and buffalo (10), hares and tortoises (11), cow's milk and rice pudding (one year), rhinoceros (12 years). Kālaśāka potherb, mahāśalka (large-scaled fish), rhinoceros, red goat, honey, and hermit foods give eternal satisfaction (Mn_3.272). This list is relatively compact, grouping plant foods loosely ('sesame seeds, rice, barley, black lentils, water, roots, or fruit') without distinguishing varieties of millet or grain.\n\nViṣṇu (Vi_80.1–80.14): Follows the same duration framework but expands the one-month plant-food list considerably, naming śyāmāka millet, priyaṅgu millet, wild rice, green gram, and wheat alongside sesame, rice, barley, black beans, water, roots, fruits, and vegetables — all of which Manu leaves as a general category. The meat sequence also differs in some steps (raurava deer at 7 months, spotted deer at 8, gavaya ox at 9, buffalo alone at 10, young goat at 11). For eternal merit, Viṣṇu specifies 'white-nosed rhinoceros' (vārdhrīṇasa) where Manu simply says 'rhinoceros.' Viṣṇu also lists specific foods to avoid at śrāddha (Vi_79.17–18): long pepper, mukundaka, eggplant, bottle-gourd, black gram, lentils, stale food, artificial salt, she-buffalo milk — prohibitions Manu does not enumerate.\n\n**DAYS**\n\nManu (Mn_3.122, 3.276–3.281): Relatively general. The monthly śrāddha falls on the new moon (Piṇḍānvāhāryaka, Mn_3.122). Any day in the dark fortnight from the 10th onward (excluding the 14th) is praiseworthy (Mn_3.276). The 13th lunar day with honey is especially good (Mn_3.273). The śrāddha should be performed three times a year — in winter, summer, and the rainy season (Mn_3.281). The afternoon is preferred over the forenoon (Mn_3.278). Night, twilight, and sunrise are forbidden (Mn_3.280). No breakdown by day-of-week or nakṣatra, and no distinction between obligatory vs. optional occasions.\n\nViṣṇu (Vi_76–78): Highly specific. Chapter 76 lists OBLIGATORY (nitya) days: new moon, three aṣṭakā days (8th day of the dark fortnight in Mārgaśīrṣa, Pauṣa, and Māgha), three anvaṣṭakā days (the day after each aṣṭakā), the full moon of Māgha, the 13th day of the dark fortnight following the full moon of Prauṣṭhapada (Bhādrapada), and the ripening of rice and barley — failure to perform on these occasions incurs hell. Chapter 77 then lists OPTIONAL (kāmya) days: solar transit into a new sign, the two equinoxes, the two solstices, the Vyatīpāta conjunction, one's natal star, and a time of prosperity; an eclipse permits śrāddha even at twilight or night (Vi_77.8–9). Chapter 78 goes further still, mapping each day of the week (Sunday → health, Monday → good fortune, Tuesday → victory, Wednesday → all desires, Thursday → knowledge, Friday → wealth, Saturday → long life), each of the 27 nakṣatras to a specific boon, and each lunar tithi from 1 to 15 to a specific benefit; the 14th day is singled out for those killed in battle.\n\n**WHERE VIṢṆU SPECIFIES WHAT MANU LEAVES GENERAL**\n\nOn foods: Manu groups all one-month plant foods into a single clause; Viṣṇu names five additional grain/pulse types (śyāmāka, priyaṅgu, wild rice, green gram, wheat), specifies which rhinoceros gives eternal merit, and provides a detailed list of prohibited foods. On days: Manu says only 'the dark fortnight from the 10th' and 'three times a year'; Viṣṇu creates a two-tier taxonomy (nitya vs. kāmya), names the specific aṣṭakā and anvaṣṭakā occasions by month, adds solar-astronomical events (solstices, equinoxes, transits, Vyatīpāta, eclipse), and enumerates specific fruits for every weekday, every nakṣatra, and every lunar tithi — none of which appear in Manu.",
